The most likely cause is that you never set the page's **`BindingContext`** to an instance of your ViewModel. Without it, `{Binding …}` has nothing to resolve against.

**Fix — set it in code-behind:**

```csharp
public partial class MyPage : ContentPage
{
    public MyPage()
    {
        InitializeComponent();
        BindingContext = new MyViewModel();
    }
}
```

**Or in XAML:**

```xml
<ContentPage xmlns:vm="clr-namespace:YourApp.ViewModels"
             ...>
    <ContentPage.BindingContext>
        <vm:MyViewModel />
    </ContentPage.BindingContext>
    ...
</ContentPage>
```

Also verify your ViewModel implements **`INotifyPropertyChanged`** (or inherits `ObservableObject` from the MVVM Toolkit) — otherwise the UI won't update when properties change after initial construction.
